  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and regulations against money laundering. Some key international frameworks include:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets global standards for combating money laundering\n- Provides recommendations for financial institutions and governments\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires countries to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigations\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Provides guidelines for preventing money laundering in banking\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Supports countries in developing anti-money laundering strategies\n\n5. Individual country laws\n- Most nations have specific anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Often requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Imposes penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Bank secrecy laws\n- Many countries require financial institutions to identify customers\n- Mandate reporting of large or suspicious transactions\n\nThese frameworks aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to disrupt financial crimes like drug trafficking, terrorism financing, and corruption.\n\nWhile these laws exist, enforcement and effectiveness can vary between jurisdictions.",
